[5] UNICEF: Worldwide cases
Date: Sat 27 Apr 2019
Source: Nation [abridged, edited]
https://nation.com.pk/27-Apr-2019/110-000-measles-cases-worldwide-reported-in-2019-unicef


More than 110 000 measles cases were reported worldwide in the 1st quarter of 2019, UNICEF revealed, adding that these figures represent a 300% hike from the same period last year [2018].

"The ground for the global measles outbreaks we are witnessing today was laid years ago," said Henrietta Fore, UNICEF Executive Director. "The measles virus will always find unvaccinated children. If we are serious about averting the spread of this dangerous but preventable disease, we need to vaccinate every child, in rich and poor countries alike."

An estimated 169 million children missed out on the 1st dose of the measles vaccine between 2010 and 2017, the UN children's fund noted. That's an average of 21.1 million children per year, with widening pockets of unvaccinated children creating pathways for measles outbreaks.

An estimated 110 000 people, most of them children, died from measles in 2017, a 22% increase from the year before [2016].

Two doses of the measles vaccine are essential to protect children from the disease. However, due to lack of access, weak health systems, complacency, and in some cases fear or scepticism about vaccines, the global coverage of the 1st dose of the measles vaccine was reported at 85% in 2017, a figure that has remained relatively constant over the last decade despite population growth.

Global coverage for the 2nd dose is much lower, at 67%. The World Health Organisation recommends a threshold of 95% immunisation coverage to achieve so-called 'herd immunity'. In high-income countries, while coverage with the 1st dose is 94%, coverage for the 2nd dose drops to 91%, according to the latest data.

The United States tops the list of high-income countries with the most children not receiving the 1st dose of the vaccine between 2010 and 2017, at more than 2.5 million. It is followed by France and the United Kingdom, with over 600 000 and 500 000 unvaccinated infants, respectively, during the same period.

