[9] Colorado: Capitol - House passes immunization exemption bill
Date: Sat 27 Apr 2019
Source: Colorado Politics [abridged, edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=638bbf37-3fad8b6c-63894602-000babd905ee-57ae464f8b10a5a8&u=https://www.coloradopolitics.com/house-passes-immunization-exemption-bill/article_8783f3b8-6921-11e9-8a60-5367e2f1fea3.html


The Colorado House passed one of the legislative session's most contentious bills on [Sat 27 Apr 2019] afternoon, but it still has a tough road ahead before General Assembly adjourns next [Fri 3 May 2019].

House Bill 1312 would create a standard exemption form for parents and guardians who want to exempt their children from immunizations for school. Parents who choose not to vaccinate their children have testified at the Capitol that they see that as an intrusion by government into their relationship with their child.

Supporters say collecting data is a necessity to track how many children are immunized in the wake of measles outbreaks across the country. The goal also is to increase participation by reducing the number of people who skip vaccinations out of convenience. Exemptions otherwise remain unchanged for those who want to exempt their children for medical reasons or personal beliefs.

To become law, the bill still has to make it through the state Senate -- where Democrats hold a narrower majority -- in under a week.

[Byline: Joey Bunch]

