[11] Summary of cases
Date: Mon 29 Apr 2019
Source: CNN [edited]
https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/health/measles-cdc-704-bn/index.html


There have now been 704 cases of measles in the USA this year [2019] the CDC said on [Mon 29 Apr 2019]. Federal health officials provided details about those cases that have not been reported this year until now including that 94% of those infected were exposed in one of the 13 outbreaks, 71% were unvaccinated, 67% are from New York City and New York state.

As many as 71% (503) of this year's [2019] USA patients were unvaccinated, 11% (76) were vaccinated with at least one of the recommended doses, and 18% (125) had an unknown vaccination status. Of those infected this year, 25 were younger than 6 months old, 68 were between 6 and 11 months old and 167 were between 16 months and 4 years old.

The new case total is 9 more than the agency reported on [Wed 24 Apr 2019] when it confirmed that the United States had reached the highest number of cases in a single year since the disease was declared eliminated in the country in 2000. Elimination is when year-round transmission of an illness is interrupted, the CDC said.

"Increased global measles activity poses a risk to U.S. elimination, particularly when unvaccinated travelers acquire measles abroad and return to communities with low vaccination rates," said a report published [Mon 29 Apr 2019] by the CDC detailing the cases of the disease reported this year [2019]. According to the report, there have been 13 outbreaks of measles this year which account for 663 (94%) of the 704 cases. An outbreak is defined by the CDC as "a chain of transmission of 3 or more cases linked in time and place and is determined by local and state health department investigations." As many as 6 of the outbreaks were in "underimmunized close-knit religious or cultural communities." That includes the 474 cases reported by New York City and New York state, which account for 67% of all of this year's [2019] cases.

The New York outbreak began in October [2018] and is now the longest and largest outbreak in the USA since 2000. In all, more than 600 cases have been reported since October [2018], mostly in ultra-Orthodox Jewish neighborhoods. It began when an unvaccinated child visited Israel, returned infected, then spread the disease to others, according to New York City health officials.

"The longer this lasts the greater chance it will get a foothold," Dr. Nancy Messonnier, director of the CDC's National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases said. She added that these communities have been targeted with misinformation that has spread.

Five cases of measles have been imported into the United States this year from Israel, which is just one of the countries where the 44 cases directly imported into this country in 2019 came from. The others are: Philippines (14 cases), Ukraine (8), Thailand (3), Vietnam (2), Germany (2), Algeria (1), France (1), India (1), Lithuania (1), Russia (1) and the UK (1), according to the CDC. An additional 4 travelers visited more than one country during the time when they would have been exposed to the virus. Of those travelers who brought measles to the United States after their trips, 88% were unvaccinated and all were old enough to be vaccinated, according to Messonnier.

According to the World Health Organization, the countries reporting the highest number of cases during the past 12 months were Ukraine (72 000), Madagascar (69 000) and India (60 000).

"Worldwide, 7 million measles cases are estimated to occur annually, and since 2016, measles incidence has increased in 5 of the 6 World Health Organization regions contributing to the ongoing risk for measles importation into the United States," the report said. The protection against the illness that results from a vaccination rate of more than 91% in children age 19 -- 35 months is at risk because of unvaccinated and undervaccinated communities, the report warned.

[Byline: Debra Goldschmidt and John Bonifield]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The header of this report refers to a mother whose 5 year old child was too young to be vaccinated, and contracted measles. Because this virus is so highly infectious, young children and immunocompromised individuals depend on the rest of society to protect them from infection and risk of severe complications. This is the basis of public health, protection of the population; it is more than the individual.
See CDC report: Patel M, Lee AD, Redd SB, et al. Increase in Measles Cases -- United States, January 1-April 26, 2019. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep. ePub: 29 April 2019. DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.15585/mmwr.mm6817e1 - Mod LK]

